The paper studies consensus processes on a complete graph, which is a classic topic in distributed computing (cs.DC). The focus is on comparing two well-known update rules, which involves analyzing the probability of reaching consensus in different initial configurations. This involves techniques from probability theory and information theory (cs.IT), as well as game theory (cs.GT) and learning theory (cs.LG). The paper also introduces a framework for comparing consensus processes, which could be of interest to researchers in social networks and machine learning (cs.SI).
